# Cursor Community Atlas â€” Agent Rules

Every future agent working in this repository inherits these rules. Treat them as binding. Where these rules conflict with a one-off task description, follow the rules and ask for clarification. SPEC.md is the canonical specification â€” see AGENTS.md for the operating manual.

---

## 1. TypeScript Conventions

**Strict mode is mandatory.** `tsconfig.base.json` enables `strict`, `noUncheckedIndexedAccess`, `noImplicitOverride`, `noImplicitReturns`, and `noFallthroughCasesInSwitch`. Do not weaken these in package-level `tsconfig.json` files.

**No `any`.** The lint rule `@typescript-eslint/no-explicit-any` is set to `error`. If you genuinely need an escape hatch, use `unknown` and narrow.

```ts
// good
function parse(input: unknown): Result<Person, AtlasError> {
  if (typeof input !== 'object' || input === null) return err(new NormalizationError(...));
  // ...
}

// bad
function parse(input: any): Person { ... }
```

**Prefer `Result<T, E>` over throws.** Every async function that crosses a module boundary returns `Promise<Result<T, AtlasError>>`. Throwing is reserved for genuinely-unexpected internal invariants. See `packages/core/src/result.ts`.

```ts
// good
export async function findPerson(id: UUID): Promise<Result<Person, QueryError>> {
  const row = await supabase.from('person').select().eq('id', id).single();
  if (row.error) return err(new QueryError(row.error.message, 'QUERY_FAILED'));
  return ok(row.data);
}

// bad â€” throws across module boundary
export async function findPerson(id: UUID): Promise<Person> {
  const row = await supabase.from('person').select().eq('id', id).single();
  if (row.error) throw new Error(row.error.message);
  return row.data;
}
```

**Exhaustive switch checks.** Use a `never`-typed default to force compile-time exhaustion over closed unions.

```ts
function widthOf(stage: LifecycleStage): number {
  switch (stage) {
    case 'lurker': return 1;
    case 'engaged': return 2;
    // ... all variants ...
    default: {
      const _exhaustive: never = stage;
      return _exhaustive;
    }
  }
}
```

**`type` over `interface` for unions and primitives; `interface` for entity shapes.** Entity types in `packages/core/src/types.ts` use `interface` for extensibility. Unions, branded types, and helpers use `type`.

---

## 2. File Organization

**One export per file when the export is meaningful.** A file that defines `LumaAdapter` does only that. Helpers used by `LumaAdapter` live in sibling files, not stuffed into the class.

**Named exports preferred over default.** Default exports break refactoring tools and obscure the symbol's name. The only exception is Next.js page/layout components, which Next requires as default exports.

```ts
// good
export function computeMatchConfidence(signals: ResolutionSignal[]): number { ... }

// avoid
export default function computeMatchConfidence(...) { ... }
```

**Barrel exports (`index.ts`) re-export the public surface of a package.** Internal files do not export through the barrel. Consumers always import from the package name, never deep paths, unless the package explicitly exposes a subpath in `exports`.

---

## 3. Naming

| Kind | Style | Example |
|---|---|---|
| Types, interfaces, classes, React components | `PascalCase` | `Person`, `BaseSourceAdapter`, `PersonCard` |
| Functions, variables, methods | `camelCase` | `findPersonById`, `signalWeights` |
| Constants (top-level, frozen, immutable) | `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE` | `RESOLUTION_AUTO_MERGE_THRESHOLD` |
| File names | `kebab-case` | `rate-limiter.ts`, `person-card.tsx` |
| Database tables and columns | `snake_case` | `person_event`, `canonical_name` |
| Inngest function IDs | `kebab-case` matching file name | `luma-fetch-events` in `luma-fetch-events.ts` |

---

## 4. Database Access

**All SQL access flows through `packages/db/queries/*`.** Adapters, workflows, intelligence services, and API routes call named query helpers. They do **not** import `@supabase/supabase-js` directly. They do **not** write inline `.from('table').select()` calls.

```ts
// good
import { PersonQueries } from '@atlas/db';
const result = await PersonQueries.findPersonById(personId);

// bad
const { data } = await supabase.from('person').select().eq('id', personId);
```

If a query you need does not exist as a helper, add it to `packages/db/queries/<entity>.ts` (see AGENTS.md "How to add a new query helper") before using it.

**No raw SQL outside `packages/db` and `infra/migrations`.** Even one-off scripts go through helpers. The exception is migrations themselves, which are SQL by definition.

---

## 5. Async Patterns

**Async functions return `Promise<Result<T, AtlasError>>`.** Never throw across a module boundary. The one exception: AsyncIterables produced by adapters (the iterator protocol does not have a Result envelope). Callers wrap with `tryAsync` at the consumption site.

**Avoid `Promise.all` over heterogeneous results.** If two parallel operations can fail independently, await them, branch on each Result, and return an aggregate error if either failed. `Promise.all` rejecting on the first failure loses information.

**No floating promises.** Either `await` or explicitly fire-and-forget via `void promise`.

---

## 6. Error Handling

**Every catch block logs with context and produces an `AtlasError`.** Silent swallowing is forbidden.

```ts
// good
try {
  return await luma.fetch();
} catch (cause) {
  const e = new IngestionError('luma fetch failed', 'INGESTION_FAILED', { url }, cause);
  this.log.error({ err: e }, 'luma fetch failed');
  return err(e);
}

// bad â€” silent swallow
try { return await luma.fetch(); } catch { return null; }
```

**Use the specific subclass** (`IngestionError`, `NormalizationError`, `ResolutionError`, `QueryError`, `WorkflowError`, `ExternalApiError`, `ConfigError`) rather than `AtlasError` directly. The subclass aids triage in logs and dashboards.

**Logged errors carry `err` as a field** (matches Pino's serializer in `packages/core/src/logger.ts`).

---

## 7. Testing

**Tests live next to source files as `*.test.ts`.** No separate `__tests__/` directory. Co-location makes refactoring trivial.

**Vitest is the only test runner.** Do not introduce Jest, Mocha, or any other runner. Vitest config is at the repo root (`vitest.config.ts`).

**Unit tests for pure logic. Integration tests for adapter normalization.** Adapter normalization tests load fixtures from a sibling `__fixtures__/` folder and assert against the normalized output. End-to-end tests are deliberately out of scope through Phase 4.

```ts
// packages/adapters/luma/src/normalize.test.ts
import { describe, expect, it } from 'vitest';
import { normalizeLumaEvent } from './normalize.js';
import fixture from './__fixtures__/luma-event-1.json';

describe('normalizeLumaEvent', () => {
  it('produces an Event record', () => {
    const result = normalizeLumaEvent(fixture);
    expect(result.ok).toBe(true);
    if (result.ok) expect(result.value[0]?.recordType).toBe('event');
  });
});
```

---

## 8. Migrations

**Migrations live in `infra/migrations/` as timestamp-prefixed SQL files.** Filename pattern: `NNNN_kebab_case_description.sql` where `NNNN` is a zero-padded integer monotonically increasing from `0000`.

**Migrations are idempotent where possible.** Use `CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS`, `CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS`, `ALTER TABLE â€¦ ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS` (Postgres 16 supports these). No bare `DROP` statements without an accompanying down-migration plan.

**Migrations run in a single transaction.** If you need DDL that cannot run inside a transaction (concurrent index creation), put it in its own migration file with a comment.

**Use TEXT + CHECK constraints, never Postgres enum types.** Easier to evolve (SPEC.md Â§3.4 #3).

---

## 9. Inngest Functions

**One function per file.** The file name matches the function ID. `luma-fetch-events.ts` exports `fetchLumaEvents` with `id: 'luma-fetch-events'`.

**Each step is its own `step.run('step-name', async () => â€¦)` block.** Inngest's durable-execution guarantees depend on idempotent step bodies. Do not perform multiple effects inside one step.

**Workflow files live in `packages/workflows/<workflow-name>.ts`.** Shared helpers live in `packages/workflows/_shared/`.

---

## 10. Adapter Pattern

**Every adapter extends `BaseSourceAdapter<TRawRecord>`** from `@atlas/adapters-shared` and implements the abstract methods (`fetchPage`, `persistRaw`, `normalizeRaw`, `idempotencyKey`). The `SourceAdapter<T>` interface from `@atlas/core` is the public contract.

**Adapter folder layout:**
```
packages/adapters/<name>/
â”śâ”€â”€ src/
â”‚   â”śâ”€â”€ adapter.ts         # the class
â”‚   â”śâ”€â”€ fetch.ts           # source-specific fetch helpers
â”‚   â”śâ”€â”€ normalize.ts       # raw -> NormalizedRecord[]
â”‚   â”śâ”€â”€ types.ts           # raw shape definitions
â”‚   â”śâ”€â”€ __fixtures__/      # JSON fixtures for tests
â”‚   â””â”€â”€ index.ts           # exports adapter instance
â”śâ”€â”€ package.json
â””â”€â”€ tsconfig.json
```

**Rate limit values come from `@atlas/core/constants`.** Never hard-code numbers in an adapter.

---

## 11. Comments and JSDoc

**JSDoc on every public function and class.** Include at least:
- One-line summary
- Parameters and return value
- One `@example` block showing realistic usage

```ts
/**
 * Compute the weighted match confidence for a set of resolution signals.
 *
 * @param signals - List of signals, weights sourced from `RESOLUTION_SIGNAL_WEIGHTS`.
 * @returns Confidence in [0, 1].
 *
 * @example
 * ```ts
 * const conf = computeMatchConfidence([{ signalType: 'email_exact', weight: 0.95, confidence: 1 }]);
 * if (conf >= RESOLUTION_AUTO_MERGE_THRESHOLD) await mergePerson(...);
 * ```
 */
export function computeMatchConfidence(signals: ResolutionSignal[]): number { â€¦ }
```

**Inline comments only for non-obvious logic.** Do not narrate what the code does. Explain *why* a non-obvious choice was made or what invariant a block preserves.

```ts
// good â€” explains a non-obvious choice
// Use natural ordering on `last_observed_at DESC` so dormant accounts
// sort below recently-active ones without an explicit WHERE clause.
.order('last_observed_at', { ascending: false })

// bad â€” narrates obvious code
// Order by last observed at descending
.order('last_observed_at', { ascending: false })
```

**Mark spec-ambiguous decisions with `TODO(spec):`** and proceed with the simplest defensible default.

---

## 12. Git Commits

**Conventional commits format.** `<type>(<scope>): <subject>` where type is one of `feat`, `fix`, `chore`, `docs`, `refactor`, `test`, `perf`, `build`, `ci`, or `style`.

```
feat(adapters/luma): implement attendee fetch and normalization
fix(intelligence/identity-resolution): correct corroboration boost bound
docs(spec): clarify embedding-match confidence formula
refactor(db/queries/person): collapse upsert + touch into a single helper
```

**One logical change per commit.** Do not bundle a bug fix with a new feature.

**Reference SPEC sections in commit bodies** when the change implements a specific spec section.

---

## 13. Dependencies

**No new dependencies without justification.** SPEC.md Â§2.3 locks the core stack. Adding `lodash`, `axios`, or any general-purpose utility requires a clear "why not the standard library / existing dependency" answer in the PR description.

**No version ranges with `^0.x`** in production dependencies. Pin to `^1` or higher. Pre-1.0 packages need an explicit decision in the PR.

---

## 14. PRs

**PR title in conventional commit format.** Match the commit style.

**PR description includes a `Spec ref:` line** pointing to the SPEC.md section(s) the work implements. If the work doesn't implement a spec section, justify in the description.

**Definition of done** lives in AGENTS.md. Re-read it before opening a PR.
